# INVARIANTS - <REPO NAME>

The per-repo registry of cross-cutting invariants: rules that must hold across many
surfaces, the single point that enforces each, and the gate that guards it. This is
the repo's hands-off memory: it counts how often each invariant has broken so nobody
tracks that by hand, and it tells an agent which invariants apply to a file before
touching it.

## How to read a row

- **Invariant**: the end-state that must hold, stated as an outcome, NEVER as a banned
  verb (a flat "never do X" rule becomes the next bug). "the k-anon floor holds," not
  "never inline `<5`."
- **Enforcement point**: the single chokepoint that, if used, makes the invariant hold.
- **Gate**: the mechanical check that guarantees it, with its tier. Tier ladder,
  earlier bites stronger: pre-commit -> local re-run -> CI (post-merge). POINT guards
  one named site; COVERAGE guarantees no site can silently omit it (only COVERAGE
  closes the per-surface-drift pattern).
- **Status**: `required-gate` (a required CI check) / `advisory-gate` (runs, does not
  block) / `point-only` (named sites; a new site can slip) / `local-green (pending
  merge)` (the check passes locally but is uncommitted / not yet a CI gate - do NOT
  label it `required-gate` or "ENFORCED" until it is merged and green on the PR;
  "prove it, don't promise it") / `advisor-only` (prose, no enforcer yet) / `to-build`
  (enforcer planned).
- **Recur**: how many times this invariant has regressed (seed estimate; keep current).
- **Detection signals**: precision-first triggers that say "this change touches this
  invariant." Favor a few reliable catches over noisy recall - an ignored signal is
  worth zero.
- **Escape hatch**: the audited override. Every guardrail is
  default-with-audited-override plus a named owner, never a flat prohibition.

